<TITLE> Ousted Thai PM Thaksin, wife face land deal charges </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BANGKOK, June 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Ousted Thai Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra will be charged with "official misconduct" this week over his wife's purchase of a prime piece of Bangkok real estate, a senior prosecutor said on Monday. The charges, due to be filed with the Supreme Court on Thursday, would be the first corruption allegations against Thaksin to make it to court since he was removed in a military coup in September. Patchara Yutithamdamrong, head of the Attorney General's office, said Thaksin would be charged with "misconduct of a government official and violation of a ban on state officials being party to transactions involving public interests". Last month an Asset Examination Committee (AEC) set up by the generals after the coup ruled Thaksin and his wife, Pojaman, had broken anti-graft laws preventing political leaders doing business with government agencies. Pojaman bought the land for 772 million baht ($22.3 million) from a unit of the Bank of Thailand in 2003, while Thaksin was in the middle of his first term in office. If convicted, he could face up to three years in jail and a 60,000 baht fine, court officials said. The AEC said it wanted prosecutors to annul the deal, return the land to the bank and confiscate the money involved. Thaksin has been in exile since the coup, staying mostly in London and Beijing. The land deal investigation is one of several against him. Last week, the AEC froze $1.5 billion in Thaksin family bank accounts, alleging he had accumulated unusual amounts of wealth during his premiership between 2001 and 2006. Thaksin and his wife have denied the charg
